</td><td><img src="/images/datel.gif" width=46 height=22 border=0><img src="/images/dateblnk.gif" width=100 height=22 border=0><img src="/images/dater.gif" width=306 height=22 border=0></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td>
	


		<td valign=top width=452><table cellspacing="4" cellpadding="6" width=100% border=0><tr><td background="/images/newsback.gif"><CENTER><H3><FONT FACE="ARIAL" color="#CB723D">Suurin</FONT></H3></CENTER>
			
		<b>Level:</b> 1<br>

		<b>Race:</b> Human<br>

		<b>Class:</b> Monk<br>

		<b>PvP Switch:</b>  Off<br>
		
		<center><h4>History:</h4></center>  I wish that I could lie to you and say that my childhood had been a happy one... But, I’m not very good at lying, and I’d have to tell someone about this eventually. <br>It started out well enough, as most things do.  I was born into a caring family: A nurturing mother, a stern, but caring father, and an older brother, Ferrin, who was intent on making a man out of me.  His intentions were good I suppose; he wanted me to fit in with all the other boys.  But I knew that some things couldn't be helped, or changed.  Ferrin was warrior, constantly surrounded by honor, and my parents' praise.  He wanted to make sure that I wouldn't bring shame to the family.  I idolized my brother, and would have done almost anything he asked.  No, I would have done anything he asked, if I only could.<br>One cool summer night my brother decided that it was time I learned how to use a bow and arrow.  <br>"Do you see the owl?" Ferrin asked me as he steadied the wooden bow and reached for his quiver.<br>"Uh-huh," I replied, admiring the bird's beauty and graceful flight.  I began to feel what the owl felt.  The wind coursed down my body as I shivered with delight.  My brother’s arrow had found his target, ripping through our chests and weighing us down.  We were losing blood quickly, thrashing our wings violently, trying to stay airborne.  I felt panicked and nauseous, blacking out as I hit the ground.<br>“Suurin?  Are you okay?”  Ferrin’s voice was shaky.  “You missed my kill.”<br>“You shot me!”  My breathing was hurried and irregular.  I was covered in sweat, and my pulse was racing.<br>Ferrin looked at me puzzled.  “What are you talking about?  I shot the owl.  Now it’s your turn.”<br>“I can’t do it.”<br>“Sure you can, I’ll help you.”<br>“I’m sorry Ferrin,” I choked out, “I can’t do it.”  We walked home in a horribly uncomfortable silence.  I hated myself for not being able to live up to my brother’s expectations.<br>I couldn’t sleep at all that night.  I heard Ferrin talking to my parents.  <br>“You can’t except him to be like you,” my mother reasoned.  “He has a gift.  He’s special.”<br>“He’s a freak, that’s what he is.”  Ferrin snapped.  I winced.<br>“Suurin would do anything for your approval Ferrin, but he can’t kill.  It isn’t in him.”<br>“I… I wish he was normal,” my brother said in the softest tone I ever heard him use.<br>“It would be nice, but some things aren’t meant to be.”  The front door slammed shut as my brother ran away from me.<br>I dressed quickly and left through my bedroom window.  Ferrin would be proud of me.  I’d prove to him that I was the younger brother that he wanted me to be.  My feet pounded down the rocky dirt trail, as my eyes scanned the forest.  A rat, something, anything that moved.  A bat.  A small bat flying low to the ground.  I picked up a few stones and started hurling them at it.  One it it’s right wing, and it toppled awkwardly to the ground, where it thrashed around, a bloody mess.  I picked up a fallen tree branch whipped the bat until I couldn’t tell what it was.  I was sobbing and could barley breathe.  I shut my eyes and kept pummeling the corpse until the branch broke.  I collapsed, and I could almost feel my heart stop beating.  The smell was so sickening that I needed to turn my head so I wouldn’t vomit on the carcass.  I found the path and began to walk home.  It was late.  Something seemed wrong though, and my already queasy stomach turned.  It smelled like…. smoke.  But something else too.  Like something was burning; or someone.  I quickened my pace to sprint.<br>“Oh God…Oh God no.” I stood in front the house that was now a flaming mass of charred wood and scorched flesh. It was on fire.  The house that I had lived in all of my life was on fire.  And my parents were…dead.  Barbarians did this.  They took whatever they wanted and destroyed the rest.<br>I needed to leave, to go someplace safe.  The only place that I could think of was the monastery.  I would study there become a monk, worshipping Quellious, and maybe finding salvation.  Then, I would find Ferrin.<br>
<p><p>
		
